# §1. Phenomenon Overview {#§1.-phenomenon-overview}

## §1.1 Phenomenon of Interest, AI-to-AI Interactions, and Our Media Ecosystem {#§1.1-phenomenon-of-interest,-ai-to-ai-interactions,-and-our-media-ecosystem}

Our chosen phenomenon revolves around self-driving vehicles communicating with one another on the roads we all commonly drive on. This phenomenon is conceptualized in the sector of self-driving vehicles as Vehicle-To-Vehicle communication, or V2V for short. V2V is a form of information transfer between AI vehicles through omnidirectional radio signals (Harding et al., 2014, p. 28). This manifests in information about road conditions, their surroundings, and different analytics. When two AI self-driving vehicles are driving along a road, they are sending V2V signals to one another and potentially any other AI self-driving vehicles in range. Furthermore, V2V implements machine learning mechanics for optimization, further distinguishing it as artificial intelligence alongside the other artificial intelligence mechanics onboard AI self-driving vehicles (Pandian, 2022). As a result of this phenomenon, an observable AI-to-AI interaction is born. We have simulated this phenomenon to explore the characteristics and consequences of these interactions in our media ecosystem. We wanted to identify any emergent behaviour that can emerge in this complex system we drive on constantly.

Although not immediately obvious, the rise of AI vehicles and the information being transferred between them through V2V has led to our roads becoming a media ecosystem. An ecosystem is commonly known as a system formed by organisms interacting with their physical environment, including both biotic and abiotic elements. In our real life roads, the biotic elements are the AI vehicles communicating with one another and the abiotic elements are the roads themselves and other normal vehicles. Dynamics of energy flow are the primary reason for this distinction; AI self-driving vehicles create the metaphorical nutrients of our media ecosystem. 

To better formalize this concept, there is a direct trophic structure comparison that we can relate to. The primary producers of our media ecosystem are the autonomous car manufacturers (original equipment manufacturers, OEM); the ones who are creating the vehicles that allow for the communication of information to other vehicles. The primary consumers are the individuals who purchase and use these vehicles. The secondary consumers are the people who review or critique the vehicles. The tertiary consumers are the ones who perform analysis of the impacts of these vehicles (traffic metrics, collisions, etc…). Lastly, the quaternary consumers are the organizations and governments forming legislation around these vehicles: what is and isn't allowed. 

Furthermore, our work leverages the nature of media ecosystems on the basis of empirical data collection, system design, and network-based approaches. These are pillars we relied on to form our conclusions and build our agent based models. This is further discussed in future sections.

To close section [1.1](#§1.1-phenomenon-of-interest,-ai-to-ai-interactions,-and-our-media-ecosystem), we wanted to disclose context surrounding research literature naming conventions related to V2V in self-driving vehicles. This is because V2V can go by other names in addition to being abstracted to broader concepts. For the sake of simplicity in our report, V2V will be the primary concept of reference, although discussion may pertain to any of the concepts listed below.

* Dedicated Short Range Communication (DSRC) is another name for V2V communication. It enables vehicles to communicate effectively with each other and their surroundings in specific short-range intervals to facilitate vehicle information (Editorial Team, 2024\)  
* Artificial Intelligence for Vehicles (AIV) is a broader concept known for applying machine learning techniques such that vehicles can perform human/superhuman actions (Li et al., 2018, p. 1). V2V would be considered a subsection of AIV or as a product of it.   
* Automated Vehicle Solutions (AVS) are "self-driving vehicles that sense their surroundings, location, and space, and that are operated without human intervention or control” (Leminen et al., 2022, p. 1). V2V would be a part of specific implementations of Automated Vehicle Solutions.   
* Internet of Vehicles (IoV) is a network of vehicles equipped with technologies with the aim of connecting & exchanging data over the Internet (Lee et al., 2016). The V2V communication that we consider uses direct radio signals to communicate, omitting the usage of the internet. This means that the AI self-driving vehicles with V2V implementations are not part of the IoV when considering our definition. However, in the real world, the implementation of V2V can vary to utilize the internet, making it flexible for our definition (Pandian, 2022).

## §1.2 Problem Statement {#§1.2-problem-statement}

	As outlined in [§1.1](#§1.1-phenomenon-of-interest,-ai-to-ai-interactions,-and-our-media-ecosystem), AI self-driving vehicles that utilize V2V communications are increasing in prevalence in road systems all across the world. This is a global phenomenon that is being augmented as disruptive market-shaping processes shift towards AI products (Sandvik et al., 2024, p. 1). At the forefront of it all, V2V is being employed to improve safety standards of self-driving AI vehicles (Harding et al., 2014, p. 7). These AI vehicles determine the safety of our roads, and as a result, V2V functioning as optimally and safely as possible is a crucial priority. 

Consequences that are unfavourable and unanticipated are the most dangerous form of consequences. The malfunctioning of V2V systems from unanticipated emergent behaviours is no exception and will always be met with **accountability** on the end of manufacturers. As the sharp rise in AI-to-AI interactions in this media ecosystem has grown, so has the potential for consequences. Our work intends to uncover these potential behaviours to further contribute to the safety of these AI systems. 

To add further, we can also examine our problem statement through the lens of sociotechnical co-production. Artificial Intelligence-powered vehicles have to abide by the many laws that pertain to vehicles, such as speeding limits, traffic lights, etc. Society influences the technological advancements in this sector, as it can influence the extent of their autonomy through conceived notions and beliefs. Our work looks at both the technological aspect of the problem and the societal. We examine the technological aspect by performing simulation studies related to the topic and examining the behaviour of the V2V technology interactions at scale. We examine the societal aspect through our communication of the discoveries which can sway public sentiment and market trends. 

## §1.3 Agent-Based Modelling (ABM) As a Suitable Approach {#§1.3-agent-based-modelling-(abm)-as-a-suitable-approach}

To describe Agent-Based modelling (ABM) as a suitable approach, we must first outline the definition of simulation studies. "A simulation study involves the use of computational models, algorithms, or systems to simulate user behaviours, interactions, or scenarios" (Baljko, 2025, CM11 p. 3). It is particularly interesting when considering complex systems, "systems composed of many interacting components (often called agents or elements) that exhibit emergent behaviour" (Baljko, 2025, CM11 p. 5). 

Returning to our described media ecosystem, we can see that this definition of complex systems fits perfectly. As outlined in [§1.1](#§1.1-phenomenon-of-interest,-ai-to-ai-interactions,-and-our-media-ecosystem), our media ecosystem comprises biotic elements (AI self-driving vehicles) and abiotic elements (human vehicles and roads) all interacting with one another through action possibilities. Furthermore, the vehicle components of our media ecosystem form AI-to-AI, AI-to-human, and human-to-human interactions, which continue to set the stage for the possibility of emergent behaviour. V2V, in particular, adds considerable complexity to the already complex ecosystem described above. Some key characteristics of complex systems that can be seen in our media ecosystem are non-linearity, emergence, interconnectedness, self-organization, and heterogeneity. These arise from the interplay of interactions discussed above. These will all be discussed in further detail in future sections with specificity to our simulation study.

To better outline the suitability for ABM, our phenomenon, when viewed from the micro, meso, or macro level point of view, finds itself at the micro level. What we describe in section 1.1 are dynamics at the individual and inter-individual levels. Fittingly, ABM is a form of computational investigation at the micro level described. There is a hand in hand relationship between using ABM for computational investigations and phenomenon/complex systems at the micro level.

To end, a common criticism of simulation studies is that they are costly and not worthwhile. But in reality, what other option exists for simulating road systems at this scale? Running our media ecosystem at the scale of our simulations requires an inconceivable amount of resources. We spawn thousands of vehicles and track thousands of collisions. This is just not possible to replicate as research in the real world. Furthermore, it would be unethical to utilize humans in our systems as they would be in active danger of collisions. ABM is a suitable alternative to omit these downsides and reject the criticism mentioned. ABM allows us to enhance rigour safety, and predictability in our work.

# §2. Simulation Design & Implementation  {#§2.-simulation-design-&-implementation}

## §2.1 System Overview {#§2.1-system-overview}

### §2.1.1 Agents {#§2.1.1-agents}

At the heart of our simulation we have our 2 agent classes. We have human vehicles and AI vehicles, respectively representing the abiotic and biotic elements of our media ecosystem. V2V is enabled for all AI vehicle agents, while human vehicles are created using a more stochastic methodology. The technical details as well as the decision-making behind the direction of these agents are discussed in [§2.3](#§2.3-agent-design). 

### §2.1.2 Simulation Environment {#§2.1.2-simulation-environment}

In modern applications, AI self-driving vehicles have predominantly been applied to the use case of driving on the highway. The affordances of highway driving allow for the systemic design of these applications relative to non-highway driving. For our simulation, we decided to replicate a 7 lane highway using a grid approach. The aforementioned agents spawn at the "bottom" and work their way "upward" through the grid. This environment is established in the initialization function of our model. Further details are discussed in [§2.2](#§2.2-simulation-environment).

### §2.1.3 Model Reporters {#§2.1.3-model-reporters}

We emphasized the empirical-driven research methodology in our approach for conducting our simulation studies. For us, data collection was an utmost priority. In our model, our model\_reporter dictionary is involved in the curation of all of our data points through every step of our model. The specific data points we are collecting as well as the rationale behind their collection is discussed in [§2.5](#§2.5-data-collection-&-visualization).

### §2.1.4 Phenomenon of Interest {#§2.1.4-phenomenon-of-interest}

Our particular phenomenon of interest emerges in our model through the previously mentioned AI vehicle agent class. We align our design of the phenomenon of interest with the explanations we described in [§1.1](#§1.1-phenomenon-of-interest,-ai-to-ai-interactions,-and-our-media-ecosystem). Technical details are discussed in [§2.3](#§2.3-agent-design). Emergent behaviour of the phenomenon is discussed in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).

### §2.1.5 Collision and Lane Detection {#§2.1.5-collision-and-lane-detection}

At every step of our model, we identify collision interactions and the movement location of agents through a thorough scan of the entire grid system. These points of interest are fundamental to our emergent behaviours and interactions. Further details are discussed in [§2.4](#§2.4-interaction-dynamics), [§2.5](#§2.5-data-collection-&-visualization), and [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).

### §2.1.6 Scheduler and Dynamic Spawning {#§2.1.6-scheduler-and-dynamic-spawning}

Similarly to our collision and lane detection, we employ a dynamic spawning system for the occurrence of agents at every step of our model. As for a scheduler, the modern mesa package version has removed the functionality for a formal scheduler. In its place, .shuffle\_do("step") is our chosen function for agent scheduling. It enacts a random activation of agents, calling their step functions. Further details are discussed in [§2.2](#§2.2-simulation-environment), and [§2.4](#§2.4-interaction-dynamics).

### §2.1.7 Limitations and Future Changes {#§2.1.7-limitations-and-future-changes}

There are not many limitations to our implementation so far, and we have uncovered a great ordeal of unanticipated emergent behaviour from our simulation already. However, we still plan on making improvements for the final version. We plan on visualizing collisions between agents, tweaking the left and right sway coefficients, conducting deeper explorations into emergent behaviour, and creating a malfunction rate for our V2V implementation to uncover more emergent behaviour.

## §2.2 Simulation Environment {#§2.2-simulation-environment}

As outlined in the overview, AI self-driving vehicle use cases primarily centre around driving on the highway. This is because the affordances of highway driving allow for improved operational design of these applications relative to non-highway driving. For our simulation, we decided to replicate our media ecosystem as a section of a 7 lane highway using a grid-based approach. The dimensions of the grid are 7 x 60, meaning that we have 7 vertical columns acting as lanes of our highway system. The 60 units of height particulate to the length of each lane of the highway. Agents will be dynamically spawned at the "bottom" of the highway and work their way "upwards" to the top. The use of quotation marks in the previous sentence occurs because we demonstrate this grid from a two-dimensional perspective. In reality, our visual demonstration is from a bird's eye view perspective with vehicles more so moving forward rather than upwards. This would mimic real life camera footage captured on highways. Lastly, when agents reach the end of the grid they would be removed from the system. This represents vehicles that made it to the end of the section of the highway that we were tracking information for. Our design principle here was to observe emergent phenomenon that arose from their time of spawn to their time of removal.

We opted for a grid based approach as opposed to a continuous space system as we liked the affordances that the grid system created. The grid based approach allowed us to easily distinguish between lanes as well as the constant space each vehicle takes, replicating our media ecosystem. We took inspiration from the Epstein Civil Violence model, a model that has a multitude of cops and citizens navigating around a grid randomly and interacting with one another (Epstein, 2002). 

For the specific technical details, we opted for the usage of the OrthogonalMooreGrid as our grid. We liked this model as it treated every 8 cells around a particular cell as a neighbour. We needed all of these squares for our implementation of V2V and perception for our agent types. The parameters passed into the Orthogonal Moore Grid were: (width, height), capacity=10, torus=False, random=self.random. Width and height were set to the described 7 and 60 default values in our initialization function. Capacity was set to 10 as a fail-safe to ensure that we could allow up to 10 agents in a cell at a time without our simulation crashing. The maximum number of agents in a cell at a time is 3, making 10 a reliable parameter since capacity should be abundant as we are not interested in setting a fixed limit. Collisions are detected by the number of agents in a cell, not through the fixed parameters of the grid. Torus was set to false as we did not want vehicles travelling between the left and rightmost lanes. This would in essence be the teleportation of vehicles, which is not realistic to our media ecosystem. Thus, the right and left most lanes represent the boundaries of how far widthwise vehicles can go. Finally, random was set as a random value generator, a parameter used internally by the grid structure.

Dynamic spawning was also used in our model to simulate the media ecosystem. For our primary simulation, we utilized a 50/50 distribution of AI vehicles and human vehicles. This distribution ensured that the cause of emergent behaviour would not be due to the number of agents that spawn. We wanted to mimic what the future looks like with the influx of AI vehicles in this media ecosystem as we were primarily concerned with AI-to-AI interactions. The number of agents that can spawn in a row ranges from 1 to 3\. The middle lane will always have a random agent spawned, while the rightmost and leftmost lanes have a 50% chance of spawning a random agent. This pattern simulates the varying nature of highway traffic conditions in the real life media ecosystem. 

Other parameters passed into our model that involve our media ecosystem were:

* ai\_vision \-  integer value that represents the radius around a cell that the AI could sense V2V signals for. This was set to 3 for our deliverable 3 implementation. This was passed in for every AI agent.  
* human\_vision \- integer value that represents the distance around a cell that the human could use for perception. This was set to 1 to limit human perception and exemplify human error. This was passed in for every human agent.  
* left\_sway\_coefficient \- float value that we implemented as a result of the emergent behaviour we examined. This value is the percentage chance that an AI would sway left instead of stay straight based on V2V signals. Default value is 0.5. This was passed in for every AI agent and is modifiable in the UI.  
* right\_sway\_coefficient \- float value that we implemented as a result of the emergent behaviour we examined. This value is the percentage chance that an AI would sway right instead of stay straight based on V2V signals. Default value is 0.5. This was passed in for every AI agent and is modifiable in the UI.  
* movement \- boolean value that acts as a toggle for if agents are allowed to move. This is initially set to true for our simulation.  
* max\_iters \- integer value depicting the maximum number of steps allowed in our model. Convergence of behaviours typically occur at 300 making it so our default value of 10000 allows for convergence.


The specific impacts of these parameters are discussed in further detail in [§2.3](#§2.3-agent-design) and [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results). 

## §2.3 Agent Design {#§2.3-agent-design}

At the core of our simulation we have human vehicles (HumanVehicle class) and AI vehicles (AIVehicle class). These agents all together represent the abiotic and biotic elements of our media ecosystem as we have alluded to throughout the report. 

### §2.3.1 VehicleAgent class (parent of AIVehicle and HumanVehicle) {#§2.3.1-vehicleagent-class-(parent-of-aivehicle-and-humanvehicle)}

VehicleAgent class is the parent class of both the AI self-driving vehicles and human vehicles. It itself is a child of the mesa CellAgent class. The main reason we approached the design of AI vehicles and human vehicles with a base class is to showcase that these agents are at their core still vehicles. This mimics what exists in real life; regardless of AI capabilities, vehicles on our roads will always fall under the main classification of vehicles. The function that VehicleAgent implements is update\_neighbors. This function provides the possible cell spaces that either agent can move to in the form of the parameter empty\_neighbors. This function also fills out neighbors detected nearby agents as well as neighborhood cells in the vehicle's vision. For the sake of simplicity, we allow agents to move to the cell directly in front of them or to change lanes by moving to the left or right of the cell in front of them. If an agent is on one of the right or leftmost lanes, they will only have 2 spaces to move to (forwards or towards the middle). 

### §2.3.2 AIVehicle agent class (child of VehicleAgent) {#§2.3.2-aivehicle-agent-class-(child-of-vehicleagent)}

In our media ecosystem, the social bot elements present are AI self-driving vehicles. Social bots are automated software programs designed to perform tasks within media ecosystems. This is exactly what our AI self-driving vehicles are, software programs that replicate human behaviour in the form of driving. The role of these social bots, rifling from the media ecosystem metaphor, are part of the primary producer. They are the vehicle systems that participate in the flow of information and form the base of our trophic structure. To outline their behaviours/goals and further illustrate their roles, we will use a goal hierarchy:

Their **low-level actions** are the atomic capabilities that we have programmed into our simulation for these agents that can occur at a single step in Mesa. They can detect neighbours using the inherited update\_neighbors function. They can also move to a cell in their empty\_neighbors parameter generated from the earlier function. Collisions would occur when two agents on the same row move to the same empty neighbour at a step.

Their **intermediate behaviour** is the decision-making and ruleset for our V2V implementation that takes place to avoid other vehicles. The V2V implementation that we have is a fundamental one. We abstracted the nuances that go into real life AI vehicles to better align with our simulation. If a V2V signal is established between AI vehicles, they will mitigate collisions by avoiding the other agent. The potential movement that can occur depends on the position of the other AI agent and the left\_sway\_coefficient/right\_sway\_coefficient values. If a vehicle has one of these values at a value of 1, they will always sway away from the other AI vehicle. If these values are set to 0, they will always stay in the same lane when detecting another vehicle. Which specific value is used depends on the position of the other AI vehicle. If an AI vehicle is detected to the left, we will use the left\_sway\_coefficient, and vice versa for an AI vehicle detected to the right. The vision attribute is also key here to denote the radius of possible agents to be detected. This was passed in from the model's ai\_vision parameter as alluded to before. 

And finally, their **high-level goal** is to get from their spawn point to the end of the grid while avoiding collisions. This correlates it back to the big picture of these AI vehicles being key for the safety of our roads.

One final note, we include the is\_middle attribute to denote if an agent was spawned in the middle. This is the value we use to observe and compare emergent behaviour trends in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results). 

### §2.3.3 HumanVehicle agent class (child of VehicleAgent) {#§2.3.3-humanvehicle-agent-class-(child-of-vehicleagent)}

The other entity involved will be human-operated vehicles. Human agents can detect neighbours using the inherited update\_neighbors function. They can also move to a cell using their empty\_neighbors parameter generated from the earlier function. Human vehicles, compared to AI vehicles do not have V2V detection and actually lack any perception. The determinant of where they move to is randomly chosen. This lack of perception is encapsulated in the vision attribute. This was passed in from the model's human\_vision parameter as alluded to before. 

The reason why we decided that human agents should differ in perception relative to AI agents is to mimic the reality that humans can't always be cognizant of every vehicle around them at all times. This will illustrate the effects of our phenomenon of interest since V2V in real life provides AI vehicles with more perception than a non-AI vehicle would. Initially, we wanted human agents to have some level of perception, but this adjustment was made to simulate the error-prone behaviour of humans in real life. 

## §2.4 Interaction Dynamics {#§2.4-interaction-dynamics}

Similarly to our collision and lane detection, we employ a dynamic spawning system for the occurrence of agents at every step of our model to simulate a real life highway scenario. As for a scheduler, the modern Mesa package version has removed the functionality for a formal scheduler. In its place, agents.shuffle\_do("step") is our chosen function for agent scheduling imposed on the model. It enacts a random activation of agents, calling their step functions stochastically. Hypothetically, if we had to mention a scheduler, it would be the RandomActivation scheduler. It is the one we initially prototyped with before realizing that Mesa had deprecated it. 

The bot-to-bot interactions that occur in our simulation are through the interactions between AI vehicles. As mentioned, they are the social bots that exist in our simulation that we wanted to explore at scale. There are two key interactions, collisions and V2V signals. AI-to-AI collisions would occur when two agents on the same row move to the same empty neighbour at a step. V2V signals would be sent and received between AI vehicles when in their distance is of 3 cells with one another and between the same or above rows. It is also important to note that collisions can occur between AI-to-humans and human-to-human. These interactions are not considered bot-to-bot however, so they have been omitted from our description here.

To highlight specifically, the phenomenon of interest emerges in our simulation through the aforementioned signals transmitted between AI vehicles. This logic, as described in [§2.3.2](#§2.3.2-aivehicle-agent-class-\(child-of-vehicleagent\)), is the amalgamation of the baseline real world V2V phenomenon. The empirical driven nature of our work is in stride with looking at this phenomenon further beyond just the interactions through collisions that occur. These investigations will be described in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results), but to preface, we initially designed these interactions in their rudimentary form. This form eventually evolved into the emergence of protective behaviour by our AI agents when looking at the system as a whole. 

## §2.5 Data Collection & Visualization {#§2.5-data-collection-&-visualization}

We emphasized the empirical-driven research methodology in our approach for conducting our simulation study and data collection. In our model, our model\_reporter dictionary is involved in the curation of all of our data points through every step of our model. Here are the following data points we gather and explanations as to why:

* step\_count \- count of the number of model steps that have occurred. The value is augmented every step of our model. It is important to note that this is not related to the number of steps agents take. As for why, we use it as a timeframe for other metrics  
* human\_count \- count of the number of human vehicles that have spawned. As for why, we want to track this to understand if certain data patterns are due to variance in human vehicle counts. We also use this value in combination with other metrics.  
* ai\_count \- count of the number of AI vehicles that have spawned. As for why, we want to track this to understand if certain data patterns are due to variance in AI vehicle counts. We also use this value in combination with other metrics.  
* ai\_ai\_collisions \- number dictating the number of collisions that took place between two AI vehicles. If 3 AI vehicles collided together this value would be augmented by 2\. As for why, this is a form of interaction we have always been interested in. We use this value to observe the efficiency of V2V in our simulation.  
* human\_human\_collisions \- number dictating the number of collisions that took place between two human vehicles. If 3 human vehicles collided together this value would be augmented by 2\. As for why, this is a form of interaction we have always been interested in. It is a value that will be compared to the ai\_ai\_collisions value.   
* ai\_human\_collisions \- number dictating the number of collisions that took place between an AI and human vehicle. As for why, this value is a frame of reference for the interactions that take place. It is not something that we have expected to be correlated with V2V as humans are not receiving or emitting signals with AI agents.  
* middle\_ai\_time\_in\_polar\_lanes \- number of middle spawned AI agents in rightmost and leftmost (polar) lanes in a single step. This value is updated every step of our function and is used to track emergent behaviour described in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).  
* middle\_human\_time\_in\_polar\_lanes \- number of middle spawned human agents in rightmost and leftmost lanes (polar) in a single step. This value is updated every step of our function and is used as a comparison with the middle\_ai\_time\_in\_polar\_lanes value, further described in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).  
* middle\_ai\_polar\_rate \- this value is obtained by dividing middle\_ai\_time\_in\_polar\_lanes by steps. It gives us the average number of middle spawned AI agents that exist in polar lanes. This value is crucial when discussing results found in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).  
* middle\_human\_polar\_rate \-this value is obtained by dividing middle\_human\_time\_in\_polar\_lanes by steps. It gives us the average number of middle spawned human agents that exist in polar lanes. This value is crucial when discussing our results found in [§3](#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results).

# §3. Preliminary Observations & Results  {#§3.-preliminary-observations-&-results}

## §3.1 Description of Results {#§3.1-description-of-results}

Throughout our simulation process we have always kept our research principles as well as our problem statement in mind. We have always understood the underlying goal of V2V in AI self-driving cars and wanted to enhance the safety benefits of them long term using empirically-driven methodologies, curating our design of the media ecosystem and agents discussed in earlier sections. This culminated in our phenomenon of interest as well as unanticipated emergent behaviour/phenomenon being expressed through quantitative metrics as well as qualitative ones which we will now be discussing. 

NOTE FOR DRAFT REPORT: We plan on digging deeper into some of the phenomenon we described below for the final report. We also plan on adding malfunction rate and seeing if anything arises from that. 

### §3.1.1 Collision Behaviour {#§3.1.1-collision-behaviour}

To begin, we had a baseline desire that AI-to-AI collisions be lower than human-to-human ones. This would align with the global consensus surrounding technology and AI vehicles (Ali et al., 2018). We designed the human agent systems to simulate the real life potential for human error in these systems when compared to robots. As a result of these assumptions and design mechanics, the anticipated behaviour of AI-to-AI collisions being lower was achieved when the simulation is run at scale. Using the collision data we collected as well as the Law of Large Numbers from mathematical theory, we can observe a convergence on the difference in collisions. Quantitively, for one model run at the 1000-step mark, we can see an AI-to-AI collisions at 982 and human-to-human at 2451\. This suggests that our V2V is meeting baseline requirements. For the deliverable 4 report we will perform more detailed statistical analysis. Graphs for this are shown below.

![][image3]  
*Figure 3 \- Graph of collisions over time displaying collision behaviour at 1000 steps*

We are omitting AI to human collisions in this analysis because that will always be occurring and is not a function of V2V since V2V is an AI-to-AI interaction.

### §3.1.2 Emergent Protective Behaviour  {#§3.1.2-emergent-protective-behaviour}

	We observed emergent behaviour unfold in our simulation as development progressed, manifesting itself as "protective behaviour" performed by AI self-driving vehicles. To summarize what "protective behaviour" is, it presents itself as the pattern for AI self-driving vehicles to approach the polar (leftmost and rightmost) lanes of our highway simulation due to the underlying AI-to-AI interactions. We decided to explore this qualitatively as well as quantitatively. Images below demonstrate qualitative aspects of this emergent phenomenon, visually seeing how these AI agents move to the "protected" lanes. Quantitatively, we wanted to compare these observations to see if it was happening for the human vehicles as well. We decided to mark both human and AI agents that spawned in the middle of our highway (lane 4\) with the boolean is\_middle. We then compared the average number of both classes of agents at either polar lane. Similar to collisions, we examined, for one model run at the 1000-step mark, we can see a middle\_ai\_polar\_rate at  
10.037 and middle\_human\_polar\_rate at 5.689. This suggests that our results are proof of the emergence of this phenomenon. For the deliverable 4 report we will perform more detailed statistical analysis. Graphs for this can be seen below.

![][image4]  
*Figure 4 \- Graph of middle spawning agent average counts in polar lanes displaying emergent phenomenon of protective behaviour*

We rightfully assumed that this emergent phenomenon was due to the implementation of V2V that we incorporated. We never specifically articulated that these AI vehicles move to polar lanes, this pattern emerged from the complexities of our system. This prompted us to explore parametrizing the V2V mechanic to uncover other possible impacts. This manifested itself in the aforementioned left\_sway\_coefficient and right\_sway\_coefficient discussed in [§2.2](#§2.2-simulation-environment). As of submission, we have not performed analysis for these coefficients and will be leaving this analysis to be performed and discussed in the final report. 

### §3.1.3 Emergent Ping-Pong Effect {#§3.1.3-emergent-ping-pong-effect}

Another interesting emergence we observed qualitatively is in the lanes that contained 3 AI agents at a time. The 2 AI agents in the polar lanes followed the protective behaviour mentioned in [§3.1.2](#§3.1.2-emergent-protective-behaviour), but the 1 AI agent in the middle would ping pong between the two, maintaining a constant distance. This "Ping-Pong" effect as we appropriately labelled, was unanticipated but insightful. It furthered our confidence in our V2V implementation and is likely part of the reason why our AI-to-AI collisions are low. Images below depict this emergence unfolding. 

Now that this emergent behaviour is uncovered, it allows us to explore this in our V2V implementation. This information would make us assign the left\_sway\_coefficient and right\_sway\_coefficient to 0 for AI agents that exist in the middle lanes. This iterative process is something we implore future V2V simulators to consider.

### §3.1.4 Implications on Phenomenon {#§3.1.4-implications-on-phenomenon}

Collisions aren't emergent behaviour, that was our base case and helped us be pointed in the right direction for the simulation design. The "protective behaviour" and the "ping-pong effect" emergences however, are concepts we deem due for further exploration. In particular, the protective patterns we uncovered, where AI agents diverge into polar lanes, is something we pose as an exploration for future researchers interested in our study. We can currently imagine this behaviours' relation to societal structures like the High Occupancy Vehicle (HOV) lanes in highway systems across Ontario. This emergent phenomenon can be explored with a macro perspective on highway rulesets and is a prime candidate for further exploration. We hypothesize that a future exists for dedicated lanes for AI and implore others to explore this fascinating concept. 

## §3.2 Unexpected Behaviours and Emergent Dynamics {#§3.2-unexpected-behaviours-and-emergent-dynamics}

As mentioned, we designed our simulation with the mechanics that we believed would best represent V2V in a complex media ecosystem consisting of human and AI vehicles. The "ping-pong effect" and "protective behaviour" emergent phenomena we're uncovered with the property of sui generis, that higher level observations cannot be broken down into their smaller pieces without missing important aspects. The smaller pieces are the baseline V2V logic we made that we assumed and designed for lower collision rates. But as a result of emergence, the higher level behaviours we found in our system were unanticipated and proved incredibly interesting. There is nowhere in the program that states that AI vehicles should converge to "safer" lanes nor is there code to handle the case where AI agents spawned between two other AI agents would ping pong between them. 

As for potential explanations, our V2V implementation is the assumed root cause. As previously discussed, we will be conducting investigations of the sway coefficients to uncover further reasoning.

# §4. Challenges & Next Steps  {#§4.-challenges-&-next-steps}

## §4.1 Development Challenges {#§4.1-development-challenges}

When implementing our simulation we encountered some development challenges. Many of our difficulties stemmed from limitations and inconsistencies in the Mesa framework. These inconsistencies related to their documentation, which although thorough, sometimes led us to blockers due to out-of-date information. An example of inconsistent documentation that we personally encountered was concerning the scheduling system which had deprecated features. We attempted to follow the docs by using the standard scheduler to incrementally move our agents, but we eventually realized that many of the functions documented for the scheduler were outdated or unclear, forcing us to search for alternatives. After researching we discovered the step\_do function in their documentation, which we ended up adopting, but this example goes to show how powerful, yet misleading Mesa’s documentation can be. 

	Additionally as first-time Mesa users, we essentially needed to learn this library from scratch which was another difficult aspect of implementing our simulation. We spent numerous hours understanding the design choices, agent mechanisms, and data visualization techniques Mesa offered. This learning curve made our initial development challenging, but once we eventually understood the library and its capabilities, this challenge turned out to be a great learning experience. 

Finally, we also encountered grid model limitations when first implementing our technical solution. The default MultiGrid space in Mesa, which is used by many User-Agent models, didn’t support the complex vehicle interactions and movements we needed for a realistic V2V simulation. To overcome this blocker, we played around with Mesa’s experimental features, particularly the OrthogonalMooreGrid that we ended up using. This grid, which is an n-dimensional grid modelled where each cell is connected to all of its adjacent neighbours, allowed us to simulate our media ecosystem more realistically.

During the development of our V2V simulation, we encountered a few unexpected challenges that led us to make modifications to our User-Agent models. At first glance, we initially classified these challenges as bugs, but after further exploration we realized that they actually enhanced our ability to study the overall emergent AI-to-AI behaviours at scale. 

	Initially, during our prototype phase, we planned to remove agents from the grid once they collided to maintain a clean simulation, however, when implementing agent removal, we encountered unexpected inconsistencies which made us refactor our models. We realized that removing agents dynamically led to instability in the model, causing issues with interaction and visualization. Specifically, when an agent was removed mid-step, other agents interacting with it would sometimes reference an already deleted object, leading to errors and crashes. Furthermore, removing agents also did not allow us to create a free flowing simulation, which led us to reevaluate our approach. Rather than removing an agent, we decided collided agents should remain in the simulation, which turned out to be beneficial. By keeping agents in the simulation post-collision, we were able to grab more data, leading to better observability when it came to analyzing AI vehicles and how they adapted to collisions. It also allowed for more interactions to occur in our simulation leading to the emergent behaviour described in section 3\. It helps refine our design methodology and our outcome driven approach.

	Overall, the challenges we encountered, particularly with agent removal, turned out to be opportunities rather than blockers. By being adaptable we were able to create a simulation that analyzed AI emergent behaviours at scale. 

## §4.2 Planned Refinements for the Final Report {#§4.2-planned-refinements-for-the-final-report}

	While we have made significant progress so far on the project, there are some additional refinements we plan to implement before the submission of DEL 4.B. These refinements aim to enhance our data visualization by providing more clarity of our findings while demonstrating more behaviours in our V2V simulation.  

	To begin, a key refinement we are aiming to make is enhancing our collision visualization, and we plan to do this by changing the colour of agents that have been in a collision. This will allow it to be easier to track how collisions unfold in real time, while illustrating how vehicles persist post-collision. By enhancing our visualization in this manner, we aim to make the behaviours easier to visualize. 

Furthermore, emergent behaviour is an integral component of our simulation since it shows how AI vehicles interact dynamically. Currently, we are analyzing two emergent behaviours, but we hope to introduce one more. This addition will provide deeper insights into our simulation.

Finally, we aim to introduce a malfunction rate to our AI agents. In the real world, AI systems make mistakes and have bugs that can cause issues, therefore to mirror this reality we aim to introduce a malfunction rate for our AI agents. Incorporating this change adds a layer of realism to our simulation, while showcasing how malfunction rates can change the number of collisions for better or worse.

# §5. Ethical & Societal Reflections {#§5.-ethical-&-societal-reflections}

This was not included in the deliverable 3 report specification, but we wanted to include some writing we made pertaining to this topic as we thought it would enhance our report in its current state. 

## §5.1 Ethical Considerations {#§5.1-ethical-considerations}

While developing our simulation, ethical considerations were always kept in mind, especially when it came to privacy and data use. We made sure not to include real world data. Unlike projects that pull from social media, news, or tracking systems, our model was built entirely on theoretical foundations and coding functionalities. This way, we avoided any issues with privacy invasion or data collection.

If we had used real world driving behaviour data, some ethical problems could have come up. If we were gathering data on how real people drive from AI self-driving vehicles, it could lead to data misuse, profiling, and unwanted surveillance. Furthermore, if we decided that was the best way to approach this problem, we would have to think about getting consent while keeping things anonymous as well as avoiding biased data collection. 

From an AI governance perspective, there is a big need for transparency in who owns the data, who gets access, and if drivers have any control over it. If self-driving vehicles become standard then there should be a solid foundation of rules to ensure secure data sharing, encrypted V2V communication, and opt-in policies for human drivers.

#### 

## §5.2 Societal Implications {#§5.2-societal-implications}

The impact of our work can be looked at the micro and macro levels:

At the micro level, our findings show that AI vehicles with V2V communication are better at avoiding accidents than human vehicles. However, they are not perfect and there are still failures. Mixing human vehicles with AI ones might lead to unpredictable issues. If self-driving cars keep improving, it might raise questions like, "should human driving behaviour be modified at the individual level?" And "if AI cars are safer, who takes the blame in a crash moment after it happens, a person or the AI?".

These concerns tie into ethical questions about AI just like the ones raised in CM18 about how algorithms shape media. The document points out that "emerging AI and deepfake technologies challenge traditional notions of authenticity, making it harder to verify truth in digital content." (Baljko, 2025, CM18) In the case of AI-driven cars, the challenge isn't just about truth. It's about responsibility. If an AI-controlled vehicle makes a split-second decision that leads to a crash, who's to blame? The human passenger? The car manufacturer? The programmers? Another issue CM18 highlights is bias in AI decision-making, noting that "bias in AI-driven decision-making can reinforce systemic inequalities" (Baljko, 2025, CM18). This raises real concerns about whether AI cars might favour certain drivers over others based on built-in risk assessments. For example, could an AI vehicle be programmed to prioritize protecting wealthier passengers over pedestrians in lower-income areas? These are the kinds of questions we need to ask as AI continues to take on more control in our daily lives.

At the macro level, our results connect to real world discussions about smart city planning and transportation policies. Maybe in the future, we will have AI-only lanes to separate self-driving cars from human driven ones. Our model also suggests that AI vehicles can form efficient traffic patterns on their own, which could reduce congestion and prevent crashes. What if only wealthy people can afford AI-driven cars? It could create a bigger gap in transportation accessibility, leaving lower income groups at a disadvantage.

This connects to the concerns raised in CM18 about the growing digital divide and how access to technology isn't equal for everyone. The document points out that "unequal access to digital media and broadband infrastructure exacerbates social and economic disparities," and the same could happen with AI-driven transportation. If only wealthier people can afford self-driving cars, they'll enjoy faster, safer commutes while lower-income communities are stuck relying on outdated, less efficient systems. CM18 also warns about the dangers of corporate control over essential infrastructure, explaining that "media ownership and consolidation limit diversity in perspectives and reduce journalistic independence." (Baljko, 2025, CM18). This could easily play out in transportation, too. If just a few major companies run AI vehicle networks, they'd have the power to control pricing, decide who gets access, and collect huge amounts of travel data. That could lead to monopolies where people have no choice but to rely on a handful of corporations for basic mobility, deepening economic inequality.

CM18 raises concerns about how powerful entities control public narratives, stating that "censorship and free speech concerns arise when powerful actors exert control over narratives" (Baljko, 2025, CM18). Now imagine that kind of control applied to physical movement. If corporations oversee AI transportation systems, they could decide who gets to travel freely and who doesn't. That could turn AI-driven transport into another tool for surveillance and social control, limiting people's freedom in ways we haven't even begun to fully consider.

Looking at a global scale, AI-driven transportation could disrupt labour markets, especially jobs like trucking and taxi driving. Millions of jobs could be lost and governments would need to step in to help displaced workers find new careers. There is also a huge risk of corporate monopolization. If only a few companies own and control AI vehicle networks, they could track movements, manipulate transportation pricing, and control access to public roads. Policymakers should focus on keeping V2V networks open-source or strictly regulated to prevent corporations from having too much control.  
These societal concerns match what is discussed in CM05 which explores human-bot interactions in media ecosystems. The document highlights how social bots and algorithmic decision-making can shape media environments, noting that "we can identify the particular firms and engineers behind specific platforms and applications, but even those software engineers have trouble predicting what their algorithms will do when released to interact with users on a platform" (Woolley, 2016, p. 4887). AI-driven traffic systems might evolve in ways that are difficult to predict, potentially leading to unintended consequences in governance and control.

Even though our goal was to view the phenomenon of AI-AI vehicle communication, AI-driven transportation systems could be misused in dangerous ways. If hacked, V2V networks could be turned into a weapon. Bad agents could spread disinformation and cause fake traffic jams, accidents, or even city wide disruptions. Imagine someone remotely controlling self-driving cars and forcing them to block roads or crash into each other. Because of this, cybersecurity should be a top priority for any real world deployment.  
Another issue is AI bias in automated traffic enforcement. If AI-controlled transportation systems, it is possible that it could unfairly target certain neighbourhoods or groups which could lead to discriminatory policing on the roads. Cities need to make sure that AI governance remains fair and transparent, or else these systems could make existing inequalities even worse.

Authoritarian governments could use AI-controlled transportation for mass surveillance. For example, If every car on the road is connected to a centralized AI network then governments could track citizens everywhere they go as well as control movement and restrict access to certain areas. This could lead to major privacy violations and a loss of personal freedom.

AI-driven transportation also has the potential to make roads safer and reduce congestion, but it also raises massive ethical concerns. If not handled carefully, it could lead to privacy violations, job losses, monopolization, and authoritarian control. The best path forward is a collaborative effort between AI researchers, policymakers, and ethicists to ensure that autonomous vehicles benefit everyone, not just big corporations or governments. Future research should focus on fair AI governance, better cybersecurity, and ethical implementation strategies to prevent misuse and maximize benefits for society.
